LAGOS  – The Lagos Environmental Sanitation Corps (LAGESC), has admonished corps officers of the Agency on field duty to embrace professionalism in the course of discharging their lawful duties in line with the State Environmental Management Protection Law of 2017. The Corps Marshal of the Agency, CP Gbemisola Akinpelu (retd) made this call at the Command Headquarters of the Agency, Bolade-Oshodi. According to her, “now that we approach the electioneering period, our officers and those on field duty are to avoid any form of interference with the process and face their assigned duties and core mandate” -Advertisement- Akinpelu read the riot act to officers to shun any form of interference in party affairs regardless of their political affiliation as it is not under their purview. Whilst urging them to maintain a high level of professionalism, she warned that any offers found wanting will be deal with in accordance with the extant rules of the civil service. Speaking further, she highlighted the need for improved professionalism among corps officers and appreciated her entire management team and members of staff of the Agency for the high level of professionalism continuously displayed in the discharge of the duties. She also noted with dismay the display of goods for sale by hawkers, street traders on the walkways, lay-bys, setbacks, gutters, pedestrians bridges, road medians, verges whilst affirming that these illegal activities hinder smooth vehicular and pedestrian movement in the State. The Corps Marshal advocated for pedestrians to make use of strategically-erected pedestrian bridges and not risk their lives to cross the highways only to be knocked down by ‘hit and run’ motorists. POLL She further urged Lagosians to shun street trading, avoid crossing wheelchair ramps of pedestrian bridges with motorcycles, be security-conscious and report any suspicious movement to the law enforcement authorities for action.